  <h1>Allergen Information</h1>
  <p>This page provides information about common allergens and how they are labeled on products.</p>

  <h2>Common Allergens</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Gluten:</strong> A protein found in wheat, barley, and rye. It's commonly found in bread, pasta, and baked goods.</li>
    <li><strong>Dairy:</strong> Contains milk and milk products. Found in cheese, yogurt, and other dairy-based products.</li>
    <li><strong>Eggs:</strong> Allergic reactions are typically triggered by the proteins in egg whites and yolks.</li>
    <li><strong>Tree Nuts:</strong> Includes almonds, walnuts, pecans, and more. Often found in nut butters and baked goods.</li>
    <li><strong>Peanuts:</strong> Not a true nut, but a legume. Peanut allergies are common and can cause severe reactions.</li>
    <li><strong>Soy:</strong> Found in many processed foods, soy is a common allergen. It's also a source of protein in vegetarian diets.</li>
    <li><strong>Shellfish:</strong> Includes crustaceans (e.g., shrimp, crab, lobster) and mollusks (e.g., clams, mussels).</li>
    <li><strong>Fish:</strong> Allergic reactions can be triggered by various types of fish, such as salmon, tuna, and cod.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Allergen Labels</h2>
  <p>Manufacturers typically list allergens on product packaging using bold or capitalized text. Always read labels carefully to ensure a product is safe for consumption.</p>
